He also revealed that his style was initially classic "Boom Bap" rap. X considered himself along the lines of an Earl Sweatshirt mixed with a little Biggie before pulling out a few of his best boom-bap verses. 
XXXTentacion also had a message for new rappers who come out attempting to replicate Chief Keef, Lil Uzi, and Lil Yachty. He said that you can't start there, you have to go back and really learn the craft then work from there. He believed it was better to learn the technical side of rapping because it helped him add versatility to his style.

snippet.title: VladStocks: How to Make Money with Dividend Stocks vs Growth Stocks (Part 8)
snippet.description:
Follow @vladstocks on Instagram 
http://www.instagram.com/vladstocks

Watch Part 9: https://goo.gl/TzfM4g
Part 7: https://goo.gl/kRktY8
Part 1: https://goo.gl/uzk15Y
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In this installment of Vladstocks, DJ Vlad breaks down dividend stocks vs. growth stocks. He explains how shareholders can receive dividend payments by electing to get paid in cash or opting for a dividend reinvestment plan or DRP (pronounced drip). This plan reinvests the dividends a shareholder earned in order to gain more stock in particular company. 

DJ Vlad then breaks down what growth stocks are and the types of companies that fall under this category. He explains how these companies don't divvy out dividends but rather reinvest the profits into the company which in turn is supposed to raise the stock price. He also remarks that despite companies like Google, Facebook, Amazon, and Netflix being growth stocks, they'll eventually begin dishing out dividends after gaining enough of a market share.

--------------

Disclaimer: DJ Vlad is not a financial advisor. Posts for entertainment only - don’t rely on for financial, tax or other advice. Get your own financial advisors. Do your own research. Make your own investment decisions.

snippet.title: Flashback: Curtis "Wall Street" Carroll is a Stock Expert Serving Life in Prison
snippet.description:
In this flashback from 2017, Curtis "Wall Street" Carroll broke down the importance of financial literacy. He said "Financial literacy is one of the biggest issues that plague our society. 90% of crimes committed are money related, yet only 1% of the programs that cater to people in prison and out deal with finance. I am here to be a solution for that, at least from my perspective."

Known as the "Oracle of San Quentin", Curtis Caroll was convicted of murder/robbery 20 years ago and was sentenced to 54 years to life behind bars at an age when most of us were busy going on awkward dates as we attempted to navigate high school.

Curtis came up in what can be considered ground zero of the crack epidemic; Oakland, California. Carroll's desire to change his circumstance forced him to educate himself and at the same time awakened a conscious he long ago buried under multiple rap sheets as a youth. 

Carroll now sees his life as an opportunity to teach financial literacy the masses, attributing crime, or the motive behind it, directly to the disconnect between financial security and most people. He compares finance to a soap opera in that he attempts to find a narrative to which people are emotionally connected to, and determines his move based on that. Salute to Curtis Carroll and Sway for an important interview. Watch above.


Source: Sway Calloway - "The Last Mile Radio"

snippet.title: Bow Wow Addresses Questionable Chris Brown Lyrics
snippet.description:
Beyond expressing confusion over what issue Bow Wow might have with him to have called him out on his new track, Chris Brown hasn't addressed the matter publicly again. But Bow Wow has apparently opened up a whole can of worms with the name drop and it is forcing him to address the question as to whether or not there is beef between them. According to what he told listeners during a visit to the Get Familiar Radio on Dash, though, It isn't even like that.

"The Brown line was like: Damn, we used to roll back in the day, bro. Remember we used to hit the club? We gotta do this s**t again. Where you at my n***a? Like, where you at bro? That's what that was," Bow Wow clarified when asked if he was willing to unpack the drama. The 31-year-old rapper explained that while the song may convey his thoughts in a manner that gives off the impression that they've been rifting, Brown was only one of a number of situations and people he touched on, and that if anything he's just gotten to wonder about why they haven't been as close as they used to be.

Bow Wow confessed that he actually just saw Brown at a party a couple of months ago. He says that he doesn't plan on reaching out to hash out the contents of the song, but does expect that they will eventually get around to speaking on it.

------------------------------

West Coast rapper X-Raided spoke to VladTV from prison, where he answered questions about gangs and how he feels like they are "parasitic organisms" that feed lies to the members. He explained that the gang is going to keep rolling whether someone is in jail or not, and the greatest accomplishment for younger members is to take the names of the OGs. 

X-Raided spoke about hiring the prosecuting attorney that had him locked up after the attorney was arrested on child porn charges. He also spoke about recording over 20 projects in jail, as well his overall rehabilitation and the revelations he's had during the later stages of his sentence.

X-Raided went into detail about his impending parole and went on to call out rappers glorifying gang culture with no real ties to a set as the most threatening influence on kids. He said upon his return home, he's taking it as his duty to "2Pac all the fake gangbangers" in hip-hop.

Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Akon Brought Energy to 80M Africans Before Proposing Puerto Rico
snippet.description:
In this VladTV Flashback from 2016, Akon discussed his "Akon Lights Africa" project that has brought electricity to millions of people in the country. After revealing that he didn't know anything about the energy industry before entering, Akon said that he soon ran into some pushback from the politics in the country. He later found a way around the situation by investing in solar renewable energy, with the help of a $1 billion loan from China.

During the conversation, Akon also explained the rich opportunities for black Americans in Africa, but he feels like many of them are too afraid to make the move, despite feeling like they aren't being given a fair chance in America.

snippet.title: Flashback: G Herbo on Almost Getting Shot in the Head, Bullet Hole in His Hat
snippet.description:
In this VladTV Flashback from 2017, G Herbo discusses moving out of Chicago and how being away from home is more conducive to him as an artist.

Herbo talked about how the negativity surrounding Chicago, particularly the Southside and Eastside respectively, is "too polluted." He said that you have to leave the house with the mentality that your life is at stake in Chicago.

G Herbo broke down how life doesn't coincide with everything he's doing now. He went on to discuss some early traumatic events in his past, such as witnessing his first murder at 8-years-old as well as a near-death encounter when a bullet missed his head by inches.

snippet.title: Flashback: Nipsey Hussle Talks Gang Decline in Los Angeles
snippet.description:
In this VladTV Flashback from 2014, Nipsey Hussle shared his thoughts on L.A. rap being popular again, revealing that he's proud of his city coming together after being segregated by gangs for so many years.

Along with that, Nipsey goes into detail about the gang injunctions set in place by the city which allowed officers to arrest gang members for just wearing a white t-shirt. He believes that people would rather go to jail for being on their hustle and making money than being targeted as a gang member without committing any crime.

Watch above.

To that point, Touré told a story of BET shelving his interview with R Kelly where he asked a series of tough questions but due to Kelly's relationship with BET the network put the interview on ice after only broadcasting it for one night.

snippet.description:

He thinks the idea of forgiveness that is associated with the Black community has been warped primarily because of slavery and the connection between the generational conceptions of God and this "warped" forgiveness is apparent.

From there, D.L. Hughley goes on to explain that he feels the Black church is "the gayest place on the face of the earth." 

Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Adrien Broner Says Daylyt is Gay, But Young Thug Isn't Gay at All
snippet.description:
In this VladTV Flashback from 2014, Adrien Broner shared his thoughts on Daylyt, Young Thug, and sexuality in hip-hop.

Broner started by watching a video where Daylyt professes his desires to become intimate with Diddy, and he was completely shocked when he saw the video.  Since he wasn't familiar with Daylyt before this interview, he truly believed the Watts, California, Battle Rapper is gay.  

In Adrien's eyes, no man should even joke about something like that if their sexual orientation isn't having a legitimate attraction for men.  

He also defended Young Thug's image and explained how the general public judges him simply because he is misunderstood. Broner acknowledged that Thug does certain things that he wouldn't do, but at the end of the day he described him as being a regular guy who is not gay.

Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Ja Rule on Why He Didn't Clap Back at 50 Cent Sooner
snippet.description:
In 2014, Ja Rule sat down with VladTV and broke down exactly why he didn't respond to 50 Cent's taunts the way he wanted to back when the two Queens rappers had serious beef in the early 2000s.

Rule said that his Murder Inc family as well as legal advisors begged him not to retaliate to 50's accusations of them being snitches and being robbed for jewelry, saying that if he were to speak on the real situations surrounding the altercation, those bars could be used against them in court, so to be safe they advised him to keep quiet.

Eventually, however, Rule addressed the situation, even bringing Dr. Dre and Eminem into the beef. Rule says he never had a problem with Em and Dre, and revealed that before 50 was in the picture, he discussed collaborating with both the Compton producer and the Detroit MC. However, they understandably rode with their guy 50 and participated in bashing him, so he was simply defending himself within the context of a rap beef.

snippet.title: Flashback: A-Town Discusses Kidney Transplant & Getting Picked On as a Kid
snippet.description:

snippet.title: Flashback: Migos Knock Out 5-6 Songs a Night in the Studio
snippet.description:
The Migos current album Culture II is laced with 24 tracks. In 2015, Quavo and Takeoff sat down with DJ Vlad and spoke about their recording process and how they can pump out so many songs. "We're in the studio every day up until the weekend. We hit the road, do shows, come back [and] get right back into the studio. We've got too many projects to put out, we've got too much and we got s**t on the radio but we gotta keep the streets fed," Quavo explained. "And keeping the streets fed is very godd**n hard."

During their talk with DJ Vlad, Quavo and Takeoff discussed the process of writing their hit tracks. According to them, they can make an entire mixtape in three days tops, creating up to five or six songs a day - they even claimed to have recorded and finished their smash "Fight Night" in only 30 minutes, while most singles take no more than 45. 

Hear about the Migos being honored by YouTube and more during our latest sit-down up top.

snippet.description:

In 2014, he discussed with DJ Vlad about catching his first charges as a teen and why imprisonment can do more harm than good. He revealed that he was influenced by people who were doing the wrong things and ended up getting arrested for the first time at the age of 13 for stealing and that he received his first juvenile charge at 15 for aggravated assault and wasn't released until two years later.

Gates says that spending those two years in juvie took his fear of imprisonment away and that many kids in the state of Louisiana have no outlet except the streets.

With the rise of cryptocurrencies such as Bitcoin, many thought leaders have shared their views on the new financial craze. A two-minute animated YouTube clip titled "Sh*tcoin and Buttcoin," breaks down Cryptocurrency.

The cartoon begins with two characters telling each other about something new they both created. They agree that "their coins" are going to be very popular.

One of the characters suggests to the other that he should purchase one of his coins for one dollar. They raise the price each time from $1 to $1,000, chanting that they're rich. Do you think the cartoon simplifies cryptocurrencies?

Watch the video above: Courtesy of NaturalNews.com/Mike Adams.

snippet.title: Flashback: Ja Rule Speaks on His Beef with 50 Cent
snippet.description:
It seems like the beef with 50 Cent and Ja Rule has been reignited.

In late 2014, Ja Rule opened up to DJ Vlad about a story of his chain getting taken and addressed 50 Cent's claim that he had a part in the incident. The Queens rapper explained that Fif wasn't even present during the incident, unlike what he told the media in the past. 

The "Wonderful" rapper said that 50 Cent loves making up stories, and debunks the notion he was intimidated on a flight they were on together. Ja said that he exchanged greetings with Fif while boarding the flight, and adds that he slept for the remainder of the time.

snippet.title: Flashback: Katt Williams Says He Started Out Doing "White" Comedy
snippet.description:
In 2014, during a very rare moment, Katt Williams sat down and revealed a little bit about his come-up in the comedy game, a story rarely heard as Williams has always preferred to keep his personal life under wraps.

He speaks of "accidentally" getting into comedy after lying to a doorman in order to get into a club for free. When told he'd go on for five minutes, and that he'd be paid if he were the funniest comic that night, Williams accepted the challenge and won. Seven years later he gave it another shot and won a competition in Oklahoma where one of his prizes was to open up for Jeff Foxworthy and a few other comics on the road.

Check out Williams' interview above.

Roc-A-Fella co-founder Kareem "Biggs" Burke opened up to VladTV about doing 4-years for a conspiracy charge after refusing to tell on people for a lesser sentence. Burke explained that he merely introduced a friend to a marijuana farmer in New York, and he was subsequently tied up in a 60 person bust and charged with conspiracy. 

During the conversation, Burke explained that he took a lie detector test to show that he had nothing to do with the situation other than introducing two people, which the DEA declined to use. He also pointed out that it was his celebrity that officials were trying to use to drum up notoriety around the case.

To hear more, including how Biggs became a born-again Christian while locked up, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Flashback: Judge Joe: James Earl Ray Didn't Assassinate Martin Luther King Jr.
snippet.description:
This year marked the 50th year anniversary since the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr., and as the last judge presiding over the alleged shooter, James Earl Ray's case, Judge Joe Brown said in 2016 he still believes "he didn't kill him." In an interview with DJ Vlad, the honorable judge says he didn't believe Ray was the gunman despite pleading guilty. Brown said, Ray, denied the murder but plead guilty because he felt it was in his best interest under the circumstances given. "He said, 'I never said I killed King, I didn't kill him. I'm pleading because of Alford.'"

Watch the full interview above

snippet.title: Taxstone Addresses Rumor that VladTV is Cooperating with Police on His Case
snippet.description:
While Taxstone awaits his trial for the murder of  Irving Plaza shooting victim, Ronald "Banga" McPhatter, he recently called into the So Shameless podcast to discuss the shift in Internet culture since being in jail. Tax spoke about the death of Combat Jack, Uncle Murda's comments about him on his yearend wrap up and the rumors that DJ Vlad has been cooperating with the police in his murder trial. 

Host Realityy Bites asked about the validity of rumors that Vlad's interviews are being used against him in court. Tax asserted as he has many times before that "Vlad is a civilian." He goes on to express that he understands street codes defining a snitch as "a person who betrays a certain lifestyle - a gangster lifestyle - who makes that vow to live that lifestyle or principles, and then they go against that code." 

He then goes on to question how under that logic Vlad could not be a snitch if he's always regarded himself as a civilian. Finally, Tax firmly states "Vlad has nothing to do with anything," and tells people to stop listening to "news" they hear on the web made by untrained journalists.

Listen to Taxstone clear Vlad's name above and get access to the full episode of the podcast at one of the links provided below: 

YouTube: https://youtu.be/mBwStNAUg2k

SoundCloud: https://soundcloud.com/soshameless/say-hello-to-the-bad-guy-feat-taxstone

snippet.title: Flashback: Kevin Gates: Prison Was Best Thing to Ever Happen to Me
snippet.description:
Kevin Gates was released from jail today after serving nine months of a 30-month bid on weapons charges. Unfortunately, this is not the first the time the Baton Rouge rapper did time behind bars, back in 2014, Kevin opened up to VladTV about being in the juvenile system when he was younger, which led to him going in and out of jail throughout his adult years. The XXL Freshman explains that going to jail as a child "took the fear of imprisonment away," and says "it criminalizes you."

When asked about facing a 30-year sentence, Kevin details how the charges racked up after he stabbed someone in self-defense. He reveals that he was being charged as a convicted felon with a firearm, which resulted in 10-15 added years. An additional charge of being around a controlled substance added another 10-15 years to his sentence. 

In total, Kevin spent 31 months in jail for his convictions, but says "prison was the best thing that ever happened to me." The Louisiana native says that it taught him respect for himself and everything around him, and adds, "it only gets gangster if necessary."

snippet.title: Flashback: Chinx Credits Stack Bundles for His Career in Final Interview
snippet.description:
In May of 2015, Chinx sat down with VladTV for what would be his last interview, as he would be murdered some nights later. The self-proclaimed "#1 Coke Boy" was always known to be rapper Stack Bundles' right-hand man and "brother," and in his last interview ever Chinx paid respect to the Far Rockaway legend who paved the way for his success.

"He definitely showed me that star power," Chinx recalled. "Everybody can't just walk into a room and just light it up. He definitely had that, and I always wanted to one day get my light up to where his was." Both slain rappers grew up with one another in Far Rockaway and began working together musically in junior high school, forming a crew called the Riot Squad. Both up-and-comers were fatally gunned down in Queens nearly eight years apart, but their legacy will live on forever as two of Far Rockaway's greatest rap artists. In this exclusive clip, he also recalled one of the few times he and Stacks didn't see eye to eye. "I remember one time I argued with Stacks. I was still in the street and Stacks was making his transition from the street to music, and there was still a lot of things we needed -- we didn't have everything as far as studio equipment," Chinx went on to tell. 

Watch the clip above.

In this clip, Lord Jamar talked about what he would do if one of his children came out of the closet. Lord Jamar has a very strong opinion about homosexuality, and that didn't change just because of the hypothetical situation. He did speak, however, about continuing to love them but he wouldn't actively support the decision. Lord Jamar noted that his house would be off-limits to his child and their significant other but that his child would be welcomed into the home without their spouse. 

Lord Jamar ended with an off subject but nevertheless interesting take on why Black people don't completely lose it with white people, and he pointed out that Black people are the original people, i.e., the parent. White people would be considered the child in Jamar's analogy, and the reason Black people have never truly lashed out against whites is based on this idea that Black people are the parents of this situation, and whites are the unruly child.

Uncle Rush urged people of color, people of other religions, and the like should not engage in hateful interactions toward anyone but remain steadfast in the fight for justice.

In this clip, R.A. the Rugged Man talks about the nature of the music business now and its inclination toward posturing up figures with large followings. Case-in-point, the "Cash Me Outside" girl and her being signed to Atlantic Records is a byproduct of poisonous celebrity culture according to R.A. He believes that this holds true for the culture at large especially when looking at Donald Trump as President. 

R.A. also discussed how he likes Azealia Banks even though that opinion is not a widespread one. R.A. broke down why he likes her, pointing to her performance quality and rhyme patterns. But he does admit that she says "ignorant and dumb sh**." For instance, her comments dissing the entire U.K. was an example of her putting her foot in her mouth. snippet.title: Isis Taylor: Jeremy Piven Pulled Out His Penis to Me at a Jordan Party
snippet.description:
In 2013, Isis Taylor sat down with DJ Vlad for a discussion about working in the industry, during which she revealed a shocking story that Jeremy Piven had sexually harassed her two years prior. When asked to share a crazy celebrity encounter, Isis proclaimed that when the 2011 NBA All-Star game was hosted in Los Angeles, she was invited to a Jordan party where she met Piven for the first and only time.

Isis stated the actor walked up to her and asked if she was aware of who he was. When she was unclear, he professed, "I’m Jeremy Piven, have you been living under a rock?” The pair had a conversation which led outside for what Isis believed was a smoke break at which point the harassment took place. "We’re talking, and I guess I’m not noticing his hands," she proclaimed.

“All of a sudden [Piven] is like ‘Look all this can be yours,’ as he points to his d**k. I look down, and his d**k is full blown out," she asserted. Isis disclosed that he ordered her “to just touch it” at which point she walks back into the party.

Jeremy Piven has recently been accused of sexual assault by an actress while working on the set of Entourage, which he abhorrently denies. Listen to Isis recount the tale above.

He said police misjudged that situation like they often do because they are human and humans are all naturally flawed.

Salley talked about how the Pistons style of play was regarded as dirty by many fans but that legends of the game often praised him and his team for playing the game "the right way." Salley also talked about his relationship with Michael Jordan which stems back to their college days when Salley was at Georgia Tech, and Mike was at UNC and how their on-court rivalry in the NBA would become one of the most highly contested in league history. Salley also talked about starting a record label during this time and how his first signing was the legendary underground Detroit group, Slum Village. He spoke about his subsequent move to Toronto in the expansion draft and how he eventually would pay the team $750K to be released from his contract to pursue a career in television. To Salley, that $750K was the price he paid in order to become a "freed slave."

In this clip, Lecrae gives his backstory from growing up in Houston, Dallas, and San Diego. He said he moved around so much because his mother was ironically searching for stability. Lecrae detailed not having a relationship with his father and told of his first time meeting his dad. He said they met at a concert a few years back and Lecrae instantly knew who he was and claimed they resembled one another from facial features to height. However, Lecrae stated that the meeting was weird. He had an idea of who his father was from stories his mother told him and the man he met wasn't quite the man he made up in his mind. He explained his father's absence as a result of drug addiction and mentioned how during a phase of experimentation with drugs (everything except crack and heroin) he used his father's addiction as motivation to ward off his own potential battle. Lecrae also detailed being molested by his babysitter when he was only 7-years-old. Lecrae talked about how the experience impacted his development and how detrimental it is being exposed to sex at such an early age.

snippet.title: Too Short on Pioneering West Coast Rap from the Oakland Streets (Full Interview)
snippet.description:
Too Short sat down with VladTV to speak on his legendary career, including being the first West Coast rapper in 1980 and being inspired by Melle Mel to write stories about Oakland. He also spoke about getting his name, selling tapes to drug dealers around Oakland, and being the first rapper to write about the pimp culture in Oakland.

During the sit-down, Too Short also delved into the early days of West Coast hip-hop and shooting his first music video, which made its debut on the wildly popular Yo! MTV Raps. Things started skyrocketing for the West Coast pioneer after a rumor started that he was shot in a crack house, and he went on to work with the likes of JAY-Z, Biggie, and 2Pac.

You can hear more of what Too Short had to say in the full interview above.

Cyhi has been credited on roughly 30 Kanye tracks. He goes onto to discuss how Kanye brings in a team of writers and creatives to help produce his artistic vision and lets the viewers know that Kanye pays well, even for the most innocuous contribution. The conversation broadens when DJ Vlad asks for Cyhi's take on ghostwriting in hip-hop. According to Cyhi, "once you've bodied rap" then a team of collaborators is necessary to compete with other genres of music. All of this despite hip-hop's insistence on rappers writing their own lyrics and telling their own stories, but Cyhi made the point that some of your favorite rappers don't have stories to carry them for 6 albums.

In this clip, D.L. Hughley goes in on the existence of God and his personal reasons for believing in a higher power. He thinks the idea of forgiveness that is associated with the Black community has been warped primarily because of slavery and the connection between the generational conceptions of God and this "warped" forgiveness is apparent. To D.L., the concept of God could be intrinsic, but considering the history of America and how religion was used as a tool of oppression, it could be indoctrination as well. Hughley points out that you'll be hard pressed finding a Black atheist which could also be a byproduct of indoctrination. According to D.L. Hughley, the Black church is "the gayest place on the face of the earth. This is ironic considering the way most Christians condemn homosexuality, but Hughley believes the church contradicts itself because when "you got to Black churches, it's women, children, and gay dudes."

Moving along, Wendy explains why she thinks open relationships are a recipe for disaster and why no one should confess to cheating unless they're caught. To hear more, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Yung Tory on Being a Rasta in Hip-Hop: I'm Not Supposed to Be Doing This (Part 1)
snippet.description:
Part 2: https://goo.gl/Abm8AX 
Part 3: https://goo.gl/WVjHWt

In this clip, Yung Tory goes in depth about his upbringing as a Rasta. Yung Tory described his childhood growing up in a Rastafarian household with both parents following the religion. He revealed having never eaten meat before in his life, his mother not wearing any makeup, and confessed that he's not the strongest follower of the Rastafarian religion but considers himself a follower of the culture. Yung Tory also broke down the contradictions he finds in his lifestyle as a rapper and his upbringing in Rastafarianism. According to Yung Tory, he's technically not even supposed to be a rapper considering the content he raps about. But he explained that he's his own person and "not like every other Rasta you walking around wearing red, gold, and green."

snippet.description:
Part 2: https://goo.gl/Xxt3jV
Part 3: https://goo.gl/8Yvigu
Part 4: https://goo.gl/NRn7pJ

In this clip, Las Vegas rapper Dizzy Wright talks about his upbringing and the lessons he learned from his mother growing up. Dizzy details how he moved quite a bit growing up due to his mother's pursuit of a career in the music industry. He said his father served a 20-year prison sentence after someone cooperated with law enforcement to lower their sentence and Dizzy's dad was caught in the fray. Dizzy goes on to discuss how his mother was left to raise 5 kids on her and her endless drive to make them [Dizzy and his brothers] into music stars. She used her experience as a former tour manager for Bone Thugs in addition to experience as a publicist to help groom Dizzy. But early on, Dizzy wanted to play basketball which he said caused friction in the household. Dizzy ultimately looks back on what he characterizes as a dysfunctional upbringing, both at home and in the music business and found a way to manufacture some success.

Famed actress Karyn Parsons spoke openly about her Sweet Blackberry Foundation, which helps bring little-known stories of Black History to light for children through cartoons narrated by the likes of Chris Rock and Queen Latifah. 

Karyn explained that she was inspired by her mother's stories of people like Henry Box Brown, who mailed his way to freedom in the mid-1800s, to bring these stories to the masses and educate children. During the conversation, Parsons also addressed the "Dolly Experiment," where black children have consistently chosen a white doll over a black doll as being "good" and "pretty" since the experiment was started in the '40s. snippet.title: Bohemia on Creating Punjabi Rap: It's Not Something I Knew I was Doing (Part 1)
snippet.description:
Rappers Bohemia and J. Hind sat down for an interview with VladTV, and in this clip, they speak about being pioneers in what they describe as Desi hip-hop. Bohemia explained that the genre was bound to come out at some point, but things took off for them specifically when they were in California.

Bohemia explained that he moved from Pakistan to San Francisco with his family when he was 14 and he didn't know any English. From there, he started really getting into Desi poetry and music, and it was by chance that his poetry sounded like rap when it was played over music.

To hear more of what they had to say, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Paul of Full Force on Beating Cancer, Lou Having Disease That Leads to Blindness
snippet.description: In this clip, Full Force recall the inspiring story behind Paul's battle with cancer. The brothers discuss their respective reactions to the news while also heaping praise upon their brother for his strength and perseverance throughout the process. When Paul was diagnosed with mantle cell lymphoma, a rare and often times incurable form of cancer, the doctor said he had two years to live. But he [Paul] detailed how his spiritual grounding, as well as discipline toward working out and diet, has kept him healthy. Lou also talks about the lengths he went to ensure the health and survival of his brother Paul by donating 6 million stem cells, an act that could've easily compromised Lou's health. But they each agreed that they are willing to sacrifice their well being for their brothers. Paul has taken his experience and started a foundation dedicated to empowering and educating cancer survivors and families, The Paul Anthony Foundation at www.palivelife.org.

Famed comedian DL Hughley talks about his experience during a radio interview with Bill Cosby.  DL was already not a fan of Cosby due to Cosby's condemnation of black comedians using the N-word.  According to DL, Bill went so far as to trying to stop the careers of Dave Chappelle, Martin Lawrence and Chris Tucker.  DL Hughley also claimed to that he had known about Cosby's alleged rapes for many years. 

During the radio interview, DL tried to stay out of the conversation but was called out by Bill for using the N-word in his act.  DL responded that he may use that word, but no young girls have ever accused him of drugging and raping them.  DL feels that it's hypocritical that Cosby's comedy was clean, but his life wasn't.

At the end of the segment, DL did acknowledge the importance of Bill Cosby's positive contribution to the racial climate of today.  DL even said that there would not have been a black President if The Cosby Show never existed.
