snippet.title: Flashback: David Banner: We're Breeding a Generation of Spineless Zombies
snippet.description:
David Banner opened up to VladTV back in 2015 about his thoughts on white people saying the n-word. The Mississippi spitter gave warning to any white people daring to say it around him, saying that "you might have some problems - physically" if you drop the n-word in his presence. 

The conversation then got deeper about black culture, with Banner saying that "hip-hop don't have no f***ing rules no more." He also added that our culture is breeding a "generation of spineless zombies" today, which you can hear more about above.

snippet.title: Damian Marley on 2Pac & Bob Marley Comparisons, Album with Nas, New Project (Full Interview)
snippet.description:
Part 1: https://goo.gl/GCphTn
Part 2: https://goo.gl/ssG1Y5
Part 3: https://goo.gl/a9qBwB
Part 4: https://goo.gl/NzWmqg
Part 5: https://goo.gl/TU5E8Z

Damian Marley, the youngest son of reggae icon, Bob Marley, and a viable star in his own light sits down with DJ Vlad to speak on his dad's legacy, the impact of Rastafarianism on his life, and what it's like working with Nas and Jay-Z.

He begins by discussing his father's legacy, though Jr. Gong was only 2 when he passed, and why the Marley descendants have a knack, for music. He speaks on the social impact Bob's music has and why 2Pac may be the only artist to have such a powerful effect on the masses. He then goes on to discuss Trenchtown and the politics of Jamaica and why he feels it is important for someone like him who is privileged to some extent, to speak up on the oppressions of others in his music. 

Getting to the music, Damian discusses his success as a solo reggae artist having received three Grammy awards in his career and working with mainstream artists Nas, Mick Jagger, Skrillex, and Jay-Z through the years. He also discloses whether or not he and his siblings would ever work on a collaborative project. 

Watch the full interview above.

snippet.title: Deon Cole: Ice Cream Truck Jingle is a Racist Song "Ni**er a Love Watermelon"
snippet.description: Comedian Deon Cole in this clip with his interview with Vlad explains his "managing your blackness" bit before going on to discuss more obscure topics. Explaining what it means to "manage your blackness," Deon says, "You can't just be black in America. You gotta manage that s**t. You can't just wake up and go outside and be treated fairly. You gotta know when to be black and when not to be." Watch above.

snippet.title: Sad Boy Loko on Linking w/ YG, "Blacks & Browns" Song Improving Relations
snippet.description:
West Coast rapper Sad Boy Loko spoke openly to VladTV about his career blowing up off of "I'm Still Here" and later with his YG collaborations "Blacks & Browns" and "Bruisin'." Sad Boy explained that he met YG in the studio, which is where they recorded the song "Don't Come to L.A.," which later led to him signing to YG's 4hunnid label. 

During the conversation, Sad Boy Loko also shared his thoughts on Donald Trump and the proposed wall separating Mexico, which he responded to by questioning why there isn't a wall in Canada. To hear more of what he had to say, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Moneybagg Yo on Waking Up With Car in the Air After Doing Xanax for First Time
snippet.description:
Full Interview: https://goo.gl/n3Y1Zd

Memphis rapper Moneybagg Yo spoke to VladTV about the upcoming arrival of his The Other Side mixtape, which currently features Yo Gotti and NBA Youngboy. However, Moneybagg Yo said he would love to collaborate with Future and Drake at some point. 

During the conversation, Moneybagg Yo spoke about quitting lean to give his fans a better performance, and he also shared why his first time with Xanax was his last. To hear more of what he had to say, including the status of his love life, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Rich Homie Quan Thinks Future Would Win in Desiigner Sound Alike Lawsuit
snippet.description:
WATCH FULL INTERVIEW: https://goo.gl/498Lh4

Rich Homie Quan shared his thoughts on Desiigner sounding a lot like Future when he first started out, but the Atlanta rapper now admits that Desiigner has carved out his own lane in the game. However, when asked about a lawsuit Future filed against Desiigner for stealing his sound, Rich Homie Quan didn't hesitate to say that Future would definitely get paid in that situation.

During the conversation, Rich Homie Quan also denied that Future's "S***" was about him, despite rumors. To hear more of what he had to say, including figuring out that the game doesn't need him, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Havoc on Feeling Validated After 2Pac Dissed Mobb Deep, Prodigy Being Mad
snippet.description:
Mobb Deep rapper Havoc spoke about being stressed out before the release of The Infamous, due mostly in part to his brother, Killa Black, being on the run for murder. He later beat the trial, but Killa Black died after taking his own life, thus inspiring the dark title of their second album "Hell on Earth." 

During the conversation, Havoc also spoke about 2Pac dissing Mobb Deep on "Against All Odds," where he rapped, "Mobb Deep wonder why a n***a blowed 'em out/Next time grown folks talk, n***a, close your mouth!" The group later retaliated with "Drop a Gem on 'Em," which was pulled after 2Pac was fatally shot. 

To hear more of what Havoc had to say, including Prodigy's thoughts on 2Pac's diss, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Baby Bash On Getting Arrested in Texas w/ Paul Wall, How They Beat the Case
snippet.description: One of the biggest artists of the early 2000's, Rapper Baby Bash stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview detailing his business acumen and trouble with the law. In this clip, Baby Bash and DJ Vlad discuss Bash's thriving legal marijuana business, California's Finest. Bash also discusses, unbeknownst to him, becoming the face of legal marijuana in Texas after getting arrested with Paul Wall. Watch above.

snippet.title: Lord Jamar on R. Kelly's "Cult": Is That Any Different from Hugh Hefner?
snippet.description:
WATCH FULL INTERVIEW: https://goo.gl/ugSZcw

VladTV provocateur Lord Jamar is back to talk about the latest pop culture controversies, and here he takes on the allegations that R. Kelly has cultivated a "sex cult." "R. Kelly is just a freak," Jamar says, "Let's not act like we haven't [been hearing] the stories for years." But as always with Jamar, it's never that simple: "If he got any white girls in the cult, you better forget about it," he says. "If they all black or Mexican, he's good...This is America baby."

snippet.title: Flashback: Mannie Fresh on Gay Tolerance in New Orlean's Rap Scene
snippet.description: During a 2013 interview with VladTV, Mannie Fresh explained how New Orleans hip hop culture has been welcoming and supportive of the gay community for a long while. "It's just a flavorful city. We just, you know--we embrace everything. We, not trippin'." He went into detail on many gay artists making bounce music and his thoughts on the term "sissy bounce."

snippet.title: Deon Cole Agrees with Chappelle: Comedians are Insecure, Miserable People
snippet.description: Comedian Deon Cole stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview discussing the state of comedy in today's world. Cole is worried about the ways in which society is limiting comedy in regards to the issues that are deemed unacceptable to talk about. Cole also discusses the insecure nature of comedians and his top 3 comedians of all time. Watch above.

snippet.title: K Koke: "Are You Alone" was Based on an OG Who Snitched on My Whole Hood
snippet.description: UK Roc Nation artist K Koke in this clip talks to Vlad about the moment he realized he may have a career in music, early British "road," or gangsta rap, and the series of events that led to him signing a record deal with Jay-Z. Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Ugly God on Girls Treating Him Different When He Became Famous
snippet.description: Last year, budding star Ugly God joined VladTV to talk about Lil B, his recorded output, and how his then-newfound fame affected his love life.  "People love social status," Ugly God opines. Watch above.

snippet.title: The Outlawz on Jimmy Iovine Claiming He Bailed Out 2Pac, Not Suge: "It's BS"
snippet.description: Outlawz Young Noble, Napoleon, and EDI Mean here talk about rumors that 2Pac never wanted the group to be on Death Row and Jimmy Iovine's claim that he bailed 2Pac out of jail. EDI Mean says he's suspicious of the timing: "You got this Pac movie that just came out and now all of a sudden y'all wanna take credit for bailing him out?" Watch above.

snippet.title: Full Force on How They Formed Their Group, Producing UTFO's "Roxanne, Roxanne"
snippet.description: The three brothers of Full Force, Paul Anthony, B-Fine, and Bowlegged Lou, joined VladTV for an interview about their New York upbringing and the early stages of their career. Here, they also speak about the UTFO song "Roxanne, Roxanne," which they produced in 1984 and which subsequently inspired a number of response songs, notably from Roxanne Shante.

snippet.title: Baby Bash on Being a Hispanic Rapper But Not Gang Related, Raised Around Blacks
snippet.description:
Baby Bash opened up about his solo success during an interview with VladTV, revealing that he made $5 million and possibly more off of his hit smash "Suga Suga." He explained that the Robin Schulz EDM remix revived the 2003 hit, but Baby Bash said owning his publishing was the key in making a lot of money off of the song. 

After declaring that "Suga Suga" would still be a hit if it was released today, Baby Bash spoke about having a string of hits including "Baby I'm Back" and "Cyclone." To hear more of what Baby Bash had to say, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Flashback: Fat Boy on What He Learned from Going to Jail, Working at Chipotle
snippet.description: Back in February, comedian Fat Boy joined VladTV to talk about growing up in Essex County, New Jersey, beginning to sell drugs at the age of 14, and what he learned from his experiences in jail. Fat Boy also talked about his longstanding beef with Chipotle. Watch above.

snippet.title: Outlawz on Kadafi's Death, People Wanting Them to Turn on Napoleon
snippet.description:
Surviving Outlawz members E.D.I. Mean, Young Noble, and Napoleon sat down for an exclusive interview with VladTV where they spoke about Yaki Kadafi's death. They all spoke about the obvious tragedy in the incident and added that it was especially bad after seeing how he was living his best life and turning things around in his final months.

During the conversation, Napoleon also spoke about his cousin being the person who accidentally killed Kadafi when they were joking around. After the tragic incident, Napoleon said members of the Outlawz were being persuaded to turn on him and he was being questioned about his loyalty on both sides.

To hear more of what he had to say, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: MoneyBagg Yo on Issues with Signing to Yo Gotti Because of Neighborhood Beefs
snippet.description:
Full Interview: https://goo.gl/n3Y1Zd

Rising Memphis star Moneybagg Yo joined VladTV to speak about his 2016 project with Yo Gotti "2 Federal," his mixtape "Heartless" blowing up, and his relationship with Gotti and CMG. Moneybagg explains that the opportunity to work with Yo Gotti was too good to turn down--despite the fact that the two are from separate parts of Memphis that historically haven't gotten along. Watch the clip above.

snippet.title: Sad Boy Loko Gives the Backstory of the Scar on His Face and His Name
snippet.description: Santa Barbara, CA representative Sad Boy Loko sat down with DJ Vlad to discuss his upbringing in SB and the misconception out-of-towners may have about his city. He reveals how old he was when he got his first tattoo as well as what they represent. Loko goes in depth about his start in music, the persistence he displayed early on and finally having his material go viral. He explains how his initial purpose for making music was simply to "feed the hood" but once his music started to gain traction outside of his targeted demographic he understood the opportunity he had in front of him.

snippet.title: Exclusive Flashback: French Montana "I'm So Special" Music Video
snippet.description: Flashback to this VladTV exclusive from 2009 when French Montana dropped the visuals for "I'm So Special" from his Coke Wave mixtape series. Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Max B's Last Music Video w/ French Montana Before Going to Jail
snippet.description: Flashback to this exclusive video from 2010 showing Max B performing "Bricks and Walls" with a young French Montana. This was the last music video Max B shot before he turned himself in for a 75-year prison bid on conspiracy charges concerning armed robbery, kidnapping, aggravated assault and felony murder. French Montana has been hinting at a possible early release for Max Biggavelli via social media, but nothing concrete has been announced. Until then, watch this clip and keep the wave alive.

snippet.title: Nasty C Thinks His Father Would Kill Him if He Did Drugs
snippet.description: South African rapper Nasty C sat down to chop it up with VladTV during his American press run. In this clip he discusses his relationship with his father and the process it took build a buzz right out of high school. Nasty C speaks about making roughly $400 a show during his early days of performing and being financially resourceful due to his father's lack of financial support in his music venture. But Nasty C considers that a character building experience. According to his father, the trick isn't to make enough money to support himself but being able to take care of his family.

snippet.title: Karl Kani: Take Away All of Nike's Black Athletes, Where Would They Be?
snippet.description: Iconic designer Karl Kani in this segment of his interview with VladTV speaks about the relationship between quality and price point in clothing, the differences amongst brands like Polo, Gucci, and Louis Vuitton, and the effect athlete endorsements have on sports brands like Nike and Adidas. As he says, "Take away all the black athletes from Nike, where would they be?"

snippet.title: Jay Morrison on Rap Music Encouraging a Get Rich Quick Mentality
snippet.description: Real estate investment teacher Jay Morrison joined VladTV to talk about the "get rich quick" mentality, the consequences of making investments relative to other ventures, and how investment requires training like any other trade. "The consequences of a real estate deal going wrong is light work compared to other consequences," he says. Watch above.

snippet.title: Mr. Dalvin (Jodeci) on Devante Being Pistol Whipped & Robbed on his Birthday
snippet.description: One fourth of the legendary group Jodeci, Mr. Dalvin sat down with DJ Vlad for an exclusive interview. In this clip, Mr. Dalvin and Vlad address the rumors floating around that Dalvin was the inspiration behind one of TLC's more popular hits, Creep. The legendary artist goes on to discuss a more somber event, going into detail of when a member of Jodeci was robbed and pistol whipped. Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Cardi B on Becoming a Dancer to Escape Domestic Violence
snippet.description: While "Bodak Yellow" is prevailing on the charts and Cardi raps of no longer being a dancer: I don't dance now, I make money moves. Back in 2016, Cardi B sat down with VladTV to talk about becoming a stripper to escape the perils of being stuck in a domestic violence situation and how it helped her in life.

snippet.title: Deon Cole on Starting Tyrese Challenge: It's Being Super Deep About Bullsh**
snippet.description: In this clip, Chicago comedian Deon Cole sits down with DJ Vlad and discusses the origins of both the #TyreseChallenge, and the #SouljaBoyChallenge. Cole pokes fun at Tyrese's ultra serious and sensual persona during the interview and breaks down why he chose to go after Tyrese even though they have a cool relationship. He goes on to discuss how Tyrese is always at the center of controversy on social media pointing out how he almost ruined the Apple deal for Dr. Dre and Jimmy Iovine.

snippet.title: Money B: If Jesus Christ Played 2Pac It Wouldn't Be Enough
snippet.description: In this clip, Money B of Digital Underground discusses his feelings about the 2Pac biopic, All Eyez On Me, and the mixed reviews the film has received. Money B believes that the movie was a success and that the inaccuracies that are present within it should not take away from the story that is being told. He talks about the scathing review that the film received from Jada Pinkett Smith who said the biopic disrespected her relationship with Pac. Money B was confused by this and wonders what her real problem is. He laters talks about the magnitude of Pac and how this film was destined to be scrutinized due to Pac's fandom. Money B claims "If Jesus Christ played 2Pac it wouldn't be enough.' Money B also took the chance to plug his book entitled "Hype Man: The Money B Story" which he implies will fill in the gaps the film left.

snippet.title: Pras: Lauryn Hill Stopped Making Albums Because She Wasn't Inspired
snippet.description: In this clip, Pras discusses Lauryn Hill's artistry and says her hiatus from making new music is due to a lack of inspiration. But Pras continued to praise Ms. Hill, calling her the epitome of an artist. He later talks about dissing Wyclef and how the Fugees reunited in 2005 for Dave Chappelle's "Block Party." Pras also touched on how some tricky energy halted the making of a Fugees reunion album.

snippet.title: Rich Homie Quan: Some Mumble Rap Sounds Good, Some Makes Me Mad
snippet.description:
WATCH FULL INTERVIEW: https://goo.gl/498Lh4

Atlanta's Rich Homie Quan joined VladTV to talk about his career taking off after the success of "Type of Way," the way rap has changed from the beginning of his career to now, and how his style is in between traditional lyricism and "mumble rap." "If you fast forward to today I would say music is more about the instrumental than the words," Rich Homie says, "I would say it's more beats opposed to the message. But I can't take nothing away from the new guys." Watch above.

snippet.title: Lord Jamar on Jay-Z, R. Kelly, Rob & Chyna, Prodigy, DMX (Full Interview)
snippet.description:
Lord Jamar is back on the Vlad couch giving his hot takes on much of the content that has been circling the media in the last couple of weeks. The outspoken emcee speaks on R.Kelly's alleged sex cult, and the implication race plays in the singer's ability to escape trouble. 
From there, he discusses Jay-Z's 4:44, and how great minds think alike because they both have spoken the need for people to stop holding the "money phone" in photos.

From there the pair speaks on Rob & Chyna's pitfalls, the loss of Prodigy, DMX's potential, the whitewashing of Black icons and more. Watch the full interview above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Tray Deee Tells Story of 2Pac Running Into Puffy and B.I.G.
snippet.description: Back in 2015,  West Coast rapper Tray Dee who spent a lot of time with the late 2Pac shared a story about him. The former Death Row rapper remembered back when Pac ran into Diddy and B.I.G.  after the Soul Train Awards. While he wasn't present for the run-in, Tray says that 2Pac and his crew claimed they stepped to B.I.G. and Puff and adds that the "All Eyez on Me" rapper was hyped up.

snippet.title: Napoleon & Noble (Outlawz) on "All Eyez on Me": It Could Have Been Better
snippet.description: Outlawz members Young Noble, Napoleon, and EDI Mean spoke to Vlad about their different reactions to the 2Pac movie "All Eyez on Me," and specify the unique challenges that come along with attempting to portray an almost mythical figure like 2Pac. The trio discussed Demetrius Shipp's portrayal of Pac, Jada Pinkett's reaction to her depiction in the film, and the fact that this time around, it was someone from within the culture--LT Hutton--who brought the project to life. Watch the clip above.

snippet.title: OMB Peezy: We Based OMB (Only My Brothers) on Durk's OTF (Only the Family)
snippet.description: Southern rapper turned California transplant, OMB Peezy stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview. In this clip, Peezy talks about the inspiration behind his name and what it was like moving from Alabama to Sacramento. Peezy also discusses catching a gun charge and being incarcerated right before he was set to have a son. He explains how the events in his life motivated his drive to follow his dreams. Watch above.

snippet.title: Havoc Discusses Mobb Deep Recording 'The Infamous', Collaborating With Nas
snippet.description: One-half of the infamous Mobb Deep, Havoc stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview detailing the rise of the legendary group. Havoc discusses how Mobb's Deep first album, "Juvenile Hell", flopped and how they were subsequently dropped from their first label. Mobb Deep quickly bounced back, signing to Steve Rifkind's Loud Records. Havoc talks about releasing "The Infamous" which included legendary track, "Shook Ones Pt. 2", instantly catapulting them to the forefront of the East Coast rap game. Watch above.

snippet.title: K Koke on Getting Shot At 100 Times Starting at 15-Years-Old
snippet.description:
British rapper K Koke in this introductory clip from his interview with VladTV talks about growing up in Stonebridge, London, and the issues he faced as a result of living there.  K Koke explains that even though he might've wanted to move away, he was unable to: "I'd rather be around the s**t I know than the s**t I don't know," he says. "Poor people have to move to another poor area. It's gonna be the same circumstances in that area." 

Pure Koke Vol.4 Out Now: https://lnk.to/ purekokevol4

snippet.title: Flashback: Transgender Producer D. Smith Says LGBTQ Issues are Worldwide
snippet.description: While Trump has recently banned Trans people for being apart of the military.  VladTV flashes back to June of 2016, trans producer D. Smith expressed her thoughts on the Orlando incident that left 49 dead and 50 injured. The two time Grammy award winner says that the LGBTQ community and its issues are "a world thing." Smith also goes on to disclose the race and class barriers that trans people face as Caitlyn Jenner has become the face of the community. She revealed that she goes into every relationship communicating that she is a transgendered person.

snippet.title: Money B on 2Pac Speaking Things Into Existence with Jail, Shooting, Death
snippet.description:
Digital Underground rapper Money B spoke about distancing himself from 2Pac after the late rapper joined Death Row. After explaining that he didn't work on Me Against the World, Money B said that he feels like the project was 2Pac's most complete album. 

During the conversation, Money B addressed the drama surrounding 2Pac in his everyday life, which Money B said he feels the late rapper spoke into existence in his songs. He then added that while working on "Wussup Wit The Luv," a Digital Underground song featuring 2Pac, the late rapper spoke about death and dying, which Money B's cousin Clee warned him about. 

Check out the full clip above to hear more of what Money B had to say.

snippet.title: Mr. Dalvin (Jodeci): Puffy Asked Which Side We Were On During East West Beef
snippet.description: Mr. Dalvin of Jodeci in this clip speaks candidly about being cool with both sides during the notorious east coast vs. west coast beef. "It was for nothing," Mr. Dalvin says, "We lost two great talented people. Two of the most talented rappers we'll probably ever see. For nothing. It could have been avoided. Like I said I was cool with Puff, I was cool with Biggie. They thought we chose a side but it was never that."

snippet.title: Deon Cole on Rich People Buying Things to See What Poor People Think About It
snippet.description:
Actor and comedian Deon Cole shared his thoughts on the Mayweather vs. McGregor fight that's set to go down on August 26, and Cole believes that Mayweather is going to "whoop" McGregor. He then went on to say that he's confused about why Floyd Mayweather couldn't pay his 2015 taxes until after the fight. Deon then added that it would be easy to spend the reported $700 million Mayweather has made during his career in just one day.

During the conversation, Deon also opened up about new money making people do crazy things, including buying everything Gucci he ever wanted when he started getting money. To hear more of what he had to say, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Baby Bash on South Park Mexican (SPM) Getting 45 Years for Impregnating 13-Year-Old
snippet.description: In this clip, Baby Bash goes in depth about a number of things. He details how Kid Frost was the person to introduce him to South Park Mexican (SPM) during a car show in New Mexico. Bash and SPM sparked up a friendship in New Mexico, prompting SPM to fly Bash out to Houston to get a sense of the scene there. Bash talked about how much he rocked with the Houston scene saying it turned him out. He details how the SPM and himself worked closely together during this time, and the interview takes a turn. SPM found himself in two separate child molestation situations. Bash reveals his interpretation of the story and what he believes to be the truth. Nevertheless, South Park Mexican is currently in prison serving a 45-year sentence for one of the child sexual assault cases.

snippet.title: Flashback: Just Blaze Compares Eminem & Jay-Z in the Studio
snippet.description: Flashback to this interview from 2013 when famed producer Just Blaze reveals how he initially met up with Jay Z after Roc-A-Fella sought him out after listening to some of his music. He also reveals the one song that solidified their relationship, and details the differences in working with Eminem and Jay Z. Watch above.

snippet.title: Tameka Foster on Usher Fans Making Her More Self Conscious After Marriage
snippet.description:
Tameka Foster spoke openly about her relationship with Usher during an exclusive interview with VladTV in 2015, and she revealed that she couldn't stand him at first. Tameka explained that Usher always wanted something cutting edge while styling him, but after both of their relationships failed, they bonded and became close.

Foster then shared how Usher made a surprise proposal when she came to the studio one night, adding that he didn't even have it planned out, as he proposed with a string that she wore for a month straight. To hear more of what Tameka had to say, including how things changed after their marriage and her pregnancy, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Havoc: Prodigy Left His Major Label Solo Deal at 14 to Form Mobb Deep with Me
snippet.description: Havoc of Mobb Deep joined VladTV for his first interview since Prodigy passed, and here he talks about growing up in Queensbridge in the 1980s, his decision to pursue music, and how he initially linked with Prodigy. Havoc describes the chain of events that led to the birth of Mobb Deep: an early record deal with Jive that Prodigy left, the first incarnation of Mobb Deep, the "Poetical Prophets," and their early meetings with Diddy when they were just 15 and 16 years old.

snippet.title: Moneybagg on Yo Gotti Giving Him $200k Cash for Signing with CMG
snippet.description:
Full Interview: https://goo.gl/n3Y1Zd

Memphis native MoneyBagg Yo stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview documenting his path from street life to the music industry. MoneyBagg discusses investing in his craft against all the odds, sacrificing personal relationships and basic amenities in order to chase the dream. He also describes how Yo Gotti was the first major artist to shout him out and the decision to sign with his CMG label ultimately. Not to mention his $220k signing bonus, in cash! Watch above.

snippet.title: Baby Bash on Skipping Town After Roommate Busted in Meth Raid
snippet.description:
Baby Bash sat down for an exclusive interview with VladTV where he opened up about growing up in Vallejo, California and being close to N2Deep rapper JT. He also shared how one of his greatest rap influences, Mac Dre, was also a huge supporter of his, adding that he could release a compilation album with their many unreleased songs. 

During the sit-down, Baby Bash also spoke about selling meth in college and getting scared out of it when his roommate was raided while he was out of state, but he avoided it by never returning. To hear more of what Baby Bash had to say, including being raised by his grandparents due to his parent's drug addiction, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Virgil Roberts: Suge Knight has a Real Chance of Beating His Trial
snippet.description: Virgil Roberts concluded his interview with VladTV with a discussion of Suge Knight's recent legal troubles and, as Roberts puts it, his "tragic" fall from his heights as a Death Row Records executive. Roberts says that Suge, who's currently in jail for a 2015 hit and run that left one dead, has a chance of getting off when his trial comes around. "I think Suge was scared. I think he was rushing out of there because he was frightened, and that's how he ran over his friend. I don't think it was an intentional act at all," Roberts says.

snippet.title: Napoleon, Edi & Noble on 2Pac Movie Causing Rift in Outlawz Relationship
snippet.description: Young Noble, Napoleon, and EDI Mean of the Outlawz came together for the first time in years for an interview with VladTV about the evolution of their relationships and their involvement in the new 2Pac movie "All Eyez on Me." Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: O.J. Simpson Pleads for Shorter Sentence During Parole Hearing in 2013
snippet.description:
Back in 2013 when embattled former NFL star O.J. Simpson speaks to the board of parole where he repeatedly apologized for robbing two men for memorabilia that was his.

He also pleads with the board for a shorter sentence, which was eventually denied until his recent parole hearing, where he was granted freedom.

snippet.title: Money B on Recording "I Get Around": I Told 2Pac I Killed Him and He Agreed
snippet.description: Money B joined VladTV to talk about recording "I Get Around" with 2Pac and his ascension to stardom. "I was like, 'I just killed you on your own song,'" Money B says. "So Pac calls me like two weeks later, and he's like, 'Yeah, you were alright.'" I was like, "'Told you.'" Watch above.

snippet.title: Deon Cole: If Rob Kardashian's Sisters were Black They Would Beat up Chyna
snippet.description: Funnyman and actor Deon Cole stopped by VladTV to discuss some contemporary stories in the culture. DJ Vlad and Deon go back and forth over the drama between Rob Kardashian and Blac Chyna, with Cole expressing his empathy for Rob. He goes on to discuss Kylie Jenner's relationship with Tyga, and whether Kris Jenner made a mistake allowing the rapper around her then 17-year old daughter. Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Aries Spears on White Neighbor Being Mad Over OJ Simpson Verdict
snippet.description:
Flashback to this interview from 2016 when former MADtv actor, Aries Spears recalled the trial of the century and how his white neighbor reacted to the verdict. Spears alludes to the enormous racial divide caused by the OJ Simpson trial and the overall outrage. Spears goes on to discuss Bill Cosby, saying he didn't want to believe the accusations telling DJ Vlad, "For the first 84 women, I didn't want to." He said, "But when it got to 92 [women], I said, 'Something's up.'"

Further into the interview, Spears goes on to talk about how race is seen differently between Blacks and Whites, police brutality, and why white people can't say the N-word around him--even when quoting a rap song.

snippet.title: Flashback: Bone Thugs Discuss 2Pac Confronting Them Over "Claiming Thug"
snippet.description:
Flashback to this interview from 2015 when legendary group Bone-Thugs-N-Harmony spoke exclusively to VladTV about working with 2Pac, and they also shared a story about the legendary emcee having a miscommunication with them over using "thug" in their name.

Wish Bone explained, "There were some words said by Pac on the box about 'Who is these dudes claiming 'thugs'?," you know how he was hot headed," and he added that "things got squashed real quick" during an in-person meeting.

The group then spoke about letting their differences go on their hit track "Thug Love," which Krayzie Bone said fans had been waiting on for a long time. He then added that they didn't expect the song to be a huge hit, because they were just following their passion for music and collaborating with artists on their terms.

Check out more of what they had to say in the above clip.

snippet.title: Andrew Schulz on Never Fighting Anyone Poorer Than Him, Too Much to Lose
snippet.description:
Famed podcaster and comedian Andrew Schulz opened up to VladTV about his thoughts on 2Pac putting himself in dangerous situations, and he explained how it's funny that 2Pac seemed to be responsible with his sex life, but not his everyday life. Schulz went on to say that he was surprised that 2Pac never had any kids considering the rumors about all the women he hooked up with.

Moving along, Andrew spoke about why he was finished having fist fights for the rest of his life, as he explained that he has too much to lose in the process and he's not concerned with being cool. To hear more of what he had to say, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Kojo Funds Getting Into Altercation with UK Police After Being Profiled
snippet.description:
UK rapper Kojo Funds opened up to VladTV about his thoughts on the lack of collaborations between Reggae and Afrobeat artists, which he says needs to change. The conversation then led into Kojo's thoughts on UK weed and how he would rank it against Amsterdam's offerings. He explained that Amsterdam's weed was more "loud," but Kojo made it clear that the UK is lacking when it comes to herb. 

During the sit-down, Kojo also answered questions on the social climate in the UK when it comes to racism, which Kojo said he's never experienced. To hear more of what he had to say, including his run-ins with police, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Zoey Dollaz Discusses "Frenemies" and Receiving Hate From His Hometown
snippet.description: Miami Native Zoey Dollaz stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview detailing his rise in the rap game and how it came to be. Zoey discusses growing up in the hood and how getting kicked out of high school fueled his drive to make it in music. He also talks about hometown hate in Miami and how he must constantly be aware of his surroundings. Watch above.

snippet.title: Andrew Schulz on XXXTENTACION: I Hope He Stops Beefing, He's a Superstar
snippet.description:
Famed podcaster and comedian Andrew Schulz revealed to DJ Vlad that he's not all that interested in rap beef. Schulz explained that he isn't a music aficionado, adding that he doesn't seek out diss tracks when he's chilling in the club. 

Moving along, Andrew spoke about why he wishes that XXXTENTACION would get past the beef phase and start focusing on his talents, as he believes that the Florida rapper could take over the music industry. To hear more of what Andrew had to say, including why he thinks younger rappers engage in beef, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Jay Morrison Discusses How He Profited During 2008's Housing Market Crash
snippet.description: Dealer turned real estate guru, Jay Morrison stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview discusses the paths toward financial freedom, equity, and the best markets to get there. Morrison and DJ Vlad discuss the market crash of 2008 and how he was able to profit during a time when most people lost money. They also go back and forth about the real estate market in general and some of Morrison's strategies geared toward creating financial literacy. Watch above.

snippet.title: Karl Kani on Migos Embracing Him and Helping Relaunch His Brand
snippet.description: Legendary fashion designer Karl Kani chops it up with DJ Vlad about the historical legacy of his brand and the difficult but necessary decisions he had to make to maintain his fashion line. Kani did not mix words as he laid out how his brand was the pioneering streetwear brand that embraced hip-hop and transcended just being something materialistic. He also touched on foreseeing the market becomes over saturated with "urban designers" which prompted him to shut down production in the United States. However, Kani remained hugely popular overseas. Kani later discussed his relationship with the Migos, and how the Atlanta based group helped him relaunch the Karl Kani brand, He even claimed the group only wore Karl Kani in their videos.

snippet.title: Flashback: N.O.R.E. - Tadow ft. Pusha T, French Montana, & 2 Chainz (Music Video)
snippet.description: Back in 2013, N.O.R.E., under the alias P.A.P.I., dropped "Tadow," a banger featuring Pusha T, French Montana, and 2 Chainz. The track appeared on the album "Student of the Game."

snippet.title: MC Eiht on His Praying Hands Face Tat, Violence Decreasing in Compton
snippet.description: In this clip, Compton legend MC Eiht chopped it up with DJ Vlad about his face tattoo of praying hands that he says symbolizes the protection he's received since entering the music business. MC Eiht wanted the tattoo to represent something positive and also spoke to persevering through life's struggles. MC Eiht went on to discuss the environment of Compton today in comparison to when he was growing up. According to MC Eiht, Compton, and the United States at large is less violent today, but he offered a caveat; it's all about perspective.

snippet.title: Andrew Schulz: Mayweather is the Best Boxer of All Time, Ali Isn't Even Close
snippet.description: Comedian and Podcaster Andrew Schultz stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview discussing contemporary issues affecting the community. He and DJ Vlad go back and forth over the fight everyone one is talking about: Connor McGregor and Floyd Mayweather. Schultz believes McGregor has no reason to fight fairly because he is very likely to lose. Watch above.

snippet.title: Deon Cole on Jay-Z Preaching on 4:44: Women will Determine if Men Accept It
snippet.description: Actor and comedian Deon Cole joined VladTV to talk about Jay-Z's 4:44, the effect of women's opinion on men's behavior, and the remedies to communities afflicted by gang violence. "As long as there's no love in the hoods, there will be gangs," Deon says. "We need to have organizations where we can go, 'Hey, you can come over here and make music.' [Where] there's love."

snippet.title: Mr. Dalvin (Jodeci) on Meeting Suge, Becoming Affiliated w/ Death Row, 2Pac
snippet.description: Jodeci's Mr. Dalvin here reflects on linking with Suge Knight and becoming affiliated with Death Row Records. On Suge Knight's reputation, Mr. Dalvin says, "I've witnessed both sides of him being angry and him being a politician. I've never witnessed him resort to violence on our behalf." Mr. Dalvin also goes on to speak about his working relationship with 2Pac.

snippet.title: Rich Homie Quan on Mumble Rap, Young Thug Fallout, Arrest (Full Interview)
snippet.description:
Rich Homie Quan sat down on the Vlad Couch to speak on his recent project Back to Basics and what he's learned from the industry. The pair discuss DJ Vlad being one of Quan's early supporters before "Some Type of Way" gained national success. The Atlanta rapper speaks on the current state of hip hop, and why he took a break because there was so much of the game, he didn't know. "I was still trying to buy everything I ever wanted in my whole life...every pair of Jordans, all the chains. I just started investing in property, mane." He talks about investing his money, buying property, and starting Black owned businesses.

Quan speaks on maturing, his fallout with Young Thug, and despite his past issues wishing Ralo nothing but success. He also addresses his recent felony charge and explains that he's not facing 30 years, and more.

Watch the full interview above.

snippet.title: Money B on Working on 2Pac's 1st Album "2Pacalypse Now", Album Flopping
snippet.description:
Digital Underground rapper Money B shared stories of his time working with 2Pac from the beginning of the late rapper's music career, including recording his first major label single, Digital Underground's "Same Song," together. 

Money B revealed that he was also in the studio while 2Pac wrote and recorded "Brenda's Got a Baby," which he says was inspired by a news article. Hit the above video to hear more of what he had to say, including how Pac used to battle guys in the hotel lobbies after Digital Underground shows.

snippet.title: Virgil Roberts on the Fall of Death Row, Beef Between Dr. Dre and Suge Knight
snippet.description: Attorney and former President of Solar Records Virgil Roberts discusses the rise and fall of Death Row Records in the early to late 90's. He discusses the falling out between Dr. Dre and Suge Knight, revealing why Dre left to go start Aftermath Records. Roberts also talks about the legal troubles that virtually bankrupted Death Row and how Tupac took death row to the next level. Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Lisa Ann: My Industry is Very Racist, No Doubt About It
snippet.description: Back in 2014, Lisa Ann joined VladTV to talk about the racism inherent to her industry. "The industry is very racist, no doubt about it," Lisa Ann explains. Watch the clip above.

snippet.title: Outlawz Deny Rumors that 2Pac Made a "Deal with the Devil" When Signing to Suge
snippet.description:
Young Noble and E.D.I. Don spoke openly to VladTV about 2Pac's relationship with Suge Knight, and they denied rumors that 2Pac felt like he was making a deal with the devil by signing to Death Row while in prison. They went on to say that they witnessed a genuine brotherhood between Pac and Suge, adding that Suge was a generous person in business and his personal life.

Moving along, the two rappers spoke about how Suge knocked down doors for rap labels like No Limit and Cash Money, and they added how they saw how a real label should be run with J. Prince's Rap-A-Lot. To hear more of what they had to say, hit the above video.

snippet.title: MC Eiht on Chicago Rappers Dissing Dead Homies: That's Bangin' on Wax
snippet.description:
MC Eiht explained why he stayed out of the East Coast/West Coast beef in the mid-'90s, as he revealed that he had a lot of love for East Coast rappers and felt like it was more of a Bad Boy vs. Death Row beef. 

During the conversation, MC Eiht spoke about how rappers never leaving their street personas behind, despite seeing some success in the music industry. He explained that it was due in part to their time spent in the streets and always feeling the need to protect their pride if they were dissed on a record. 

To hear more of what MC Eiht had to say, including his thoughts on Chicago rappers dissing their rivals' dead homies, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Virgil Roberts Details Suge Shooting at 2 Men in Their Studio, Making Them Undress
snippet.description: Attorney and former President of Solar Records Virgil Roberts stopped by VladTV to discuss some of the crazier events regarding Death Row Records and Suge Knight. In this exclusive interview, Roberts discusses Suge playing into the image of being a gangsta, even though that was not the case in reality. He discusses Suge infamously shooting at and forcing the Stanley brothers to undress in the Solar Records studio in a criminal case that would later be the reason he spent nine years in jail following 2Pac's death. Watch above.

snippet.title: The Outlawz: If We Paid Attention to Everything Said About 2Pac We'd be Dead
snippet.description: Outlawz members E.D.I. Mean, and Young Noble returned to VladTV to talk about the recent string of artists who have co-opted 2Pac's name. Vlad brings up Boosie, who recently announced an album called "BooPac," to which Young Noble says, "If you've ever been to the south, Boosie's Pac down there...Pac is the benchmark. If you're striving for greatness, universal love, the streets, if you want all that love, you gotta strive to that Pac level." Watch above.

snippet.title: MoneyBagg Yo on Sleeping on the Floor because He Invested All His Money in Music
snippet.description:
Full Interview: https://goo.gl/n3Y1Zd

Memphis rapper Moneybagg Yo joined VladTV to talk about the early stages of his career, his first big music-related pay day, and the state of Memphis radio. One of the most prominent characteristics of Moneybagg's music is its range, and he spoke about it here: "My end goal is to motivate the hoods all over," he says, "I'm touching every level. The struggle, the club feel, the turnt feel. One stop shop."

snippet.title: Deon Cole Discusses How 'Black-ish' is this Generation's Cosby Show
snippet.description: Deon Cole, best known for his roles in Black-ish and more, sat down with DJ Vlad for an exclusive interview for an exclusive interview. In this clip, Cole discusses why he believes Black-ish has quickly become this generation's Cosby Show, highlighting positivity and success in the black community. He goes on to stress the importance of balance in how black people are portrayed in television. Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Sisqo on if He Lives Off Success of "Thong Song"
snippet.description: Back in 2014, Sisqo talked about the financial impact of his "Thong Song."  Asked if he was still riding the success of "Thong Song" 13 years later, Sisqo said, "I mean, technically I didn't have to go to work. But I'm still an active member of my group Dru Hill."

snippet.title: Virgil Roberts on Suge's "Situation" with Eazy- E, Jimmy Iovine Giving Dre $1M
snippet.description:
Famed music executive and attorney Virgil Roberts spoke openly to VladTV about the making of Dr. Dre's highly acclaimed The Chronic album, which he said many labels didn't want to touch after an incident surrounding Ice-T's Cop Killer. However, things changed and Jimmy Iovine offered Suge Knight $1 million for the album. 

During the conversation, Virgil spoke about Suge admitting to pushing Eazy-E into signing Dr. Dre's release papers from Ruthless Records, but he added that he didn't know exactly what went on in the room. To hear more of what he had to say, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Outlawz on 2Pac Getting Shot in Vegas, His Last Words Being "F*** The Police"
snippet.description: Legendary West Coast rap group Outlawz stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview detailing the infamous East Coast vs. West Coast rap beef, and how it spiraled out of control. Outlawz discuss 2Pac's plans to end the beef once and for all with his One Nation project that united East Coast and West COast rappers under one album. They always discuss what in all likelihood was Pac's last words and what they were. Watch above.

snippet.title: MC Eiht on Rappers Calling Themselves 2Pac: It's Never West Coast Rappers
snippet.description: MC Eiht in this segment of his interview with VladTV confronts the new phenomenon of modern-day rappers calling themselves the "New Pac" or variations thereof. Eiht and Vlad note that it's everyone but west coast rappers that co-opt Pac's legacy, citing Troy Ave, Boosie BadAzz, and Young Thug. "I don't know if it's because people wanna live off his legacy," MC Eiht says, "But you can be hard in your own right...I've never had the feeling of wanting to call myself the next Eazy-E or the next Cube, even when I looked up to them." Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Lord Jamar on How R. Kelly's Fame Influenced Child Sex Scandal
snippet.description: As news surfaces alleging that R. Kelly makes young women join a cult. VladTV looks back on an interview with Lord Jamar from 2016, where the rapper suggests the singer's fame is enticing to his alleged victims. His lifestyle and musical notoriety factors into reasons Kelly has been able to win a court case and rose above the allegations to some degree.

snippet.title: Andrew Schulz: The Warriors are the Greatest Losers in NBA History
snippet.description: In this clip, Andrew Schulz sat down with DJ Vlad to discuss the NBA Finals and some of the more pressing topics concerning pro-hoops. Schulz makes the bold claim of calling the Warriors the league's "greatest losers" along with likening Kevin Durant's first title to a kid losing his virginity to a hooker. Schulz also offered his two cents on Kevin Durant's claim that Kyrie Irving is a better player than Allen Iverson by saying that's an accurate comparison yet Iverson was more of a defensive force. Andrew Schulz also took this time to heap praise upon LeBron James calling him the greatest teammate and motivator of all time. He also believes LeBron should win the Most Valuable Player Award every year he continues to play in the league and he backed up his claim by laying out LeBron's on-court productivity along with his intangible attributes. Despite the praise he gave to LeBron, Andrew Schulz conceded that Jordan remains the GOAT and goes on to call his "Airness" a sociopathic competitor. According to Schulz, MJ's killer instinct is what separates him from LeBron, and everyone else. He attributed much of this lack of killer instinct to the millennial generation's need to be liked going as far as to say we are "creating a generation of p***ies."

snippet.title: Outlawz Deny 2Pac Shot Himself at Quad Studios: Edi Saw the Bullet Wound
snippet.description:
Young Noble and E.D.I. Mean of the Outlawz shared their thoughts on Funk Flex recently dissing 2Pac and claiming that the late rapper shot himself at Quad Studios. Both Outlawz members denied that Pac could've ever shot himself after looking at the wound, and E.D.I. Mean says that Flex diminished his reputation with his comments.
During the conversation, the Outlawz also spoke on being told by publicists that they were being blackballed by someone at Hot 97, the same company Flex has worked at for years. You can hear more of what they had to say above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Lil Cease on Biggie and 2Pac Confrontation at Soul Train Awards
snippet.description:
In 2014, the Mafia Dons, formally known as Junior M.A.F.I.A, dropped by VladTV to talk about some of the events of their career. Lil Cease spoke up about arguing with 2Pac while he was in NYC. When asked if they heard the Outlawz smoked 2Pac's ashes, they say they have and are sure they did it out of love, but could never see themselves smoking Biggie's ashes.

Watch the clip above.

snippet.title: Mr. Dalvin (Jodeci) on K-Ci Pointing Gun at Him Over a Girl During 1st Meeting
snippet.description:
Mr. Dalvin of Jodeci fame spoke about the group's beginnings during an interview with VladTV, where he revealed that Jodeci was signed after their first day in New York looking for a deal. He explained that after finessing their way into MCA, they started singing acapella for an A&R, which led to them singing for Heavy D and Andre Harrell, who later signed them.

Moving along, Mr. Dalvin spoke about becoming best friends with K-Ci despite the famed singer pulling a gun on him the first night they ever met. To hear more, including why Mr. Dalvin said Jodeci stopped recording music together, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Napoleon (Outlawz): Suge Showed Me Bullet Wounds on His Head & Body After 2Pac Murder
snippet.description: Napoleon of the Outlawz in this clip with his interview with VladTV speaks about the rumors that 2Pac and Suge Knight had a falling out towards the end of Pac's life, and that Suge was somehow involved in Pac's murder. "I knew Suge had nothing to do with 2Pac's murder," Napoleon says, "They tried to kill him too." Napoleon and Vlad also tackle questions related to Trump and Islam.

snippet.title: Andrew Schulz Says Vlad isn't a Culture Vulture, He's a "Culture Lioness"
snippet.description: Comedian and podcast host Andrew Schulz joined VladTV to talk about being called a culture vulture and what a culture vulture really is. "The problem with the term is we use it derogatorily. It's used to punish. As if it's a bad thing to be a capitalist. In America, everybody here is a culture vulture," he says. Watch above.

snippet.title: Havoc on Forming Mobb Deep, Creating Classic Albums, Losing Prodigy (Full Interview)
snippet.description:
After the untimely death of Prodigy, DJ Vlad sits down with his longtime friend and the other half of Mobb Deep, Havoc. Havoc details what it was like growing up in Queensbridge, their first rap names, and reveals Prodigy turned down a deal to work with him at first. The producer then goes on to talk about making their first album, Prodigy teaching him how to sample and them getting a deal at LOUD records.

Throughout the conversation Havoc discusses some of the milestones in their career from the 'Hennesy' shirts, creating "Shook Ones," dissing 2Pac before his death, their beef with Jay-Z, and what it was like seeing Lil Kim write her "Quiet Storm" verse. Hav also speaks on the rumor of P choking on an egg and the cause of his death before looking back on the legacy that they left in hip hop.

Listen to Havoc pay respect to his brother above.

snippet.title: Flashback: D12 on People Thinking Eminem Was Black After First Listening to Him
snippet.description:
Flashback to this interview from 2015 when Bizarre, Kuniva, and Swifty McVay spoke exclusively to VladTV about the formation of D12, as they told us that it was late Detroit rapper Proof who came up with the idea for the group.

When speaking about how they all met, Kuniva revealed that there was a clothing store—The Hip Hop Shop—that hosted open mic cyphers for rappers that they all attended. Swifty added that the store was where they met Eminem, who blew them away with his skills, and he later ended up joining D12.

Speaking more about Eminem, Kuniva said that a lot of people mistook the "Lose Yourself" lyricist for Black when he first released The Slim Shady LP, and he added, "it was extra crazy" when they found out he was a White rapper.

Check out more of what D12 had to say during the above interview, including other rappers who came up at The Hip Hop Shop.

snippet.title: MoneyBagg Yo on His Brother's Death Changing Him, Memphis Hypnotized by Hatred
snippet.description:
Full Interview: https://goo.gl/n3Y1Zd

Memphis up and comer MoneyBagg Yo stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview detailing his childhood and decision to pursue music ultimately. MoneyBagg recalls times when he spent his last dollar on studio time while others he knew were gambling or spending their money a different way. He also discusses hatred within his hometown and how he avoids it. Watch above.

snippet.title: Chris Carroll: 2Pac Hating Police Didn't Mean We Didn't Want to Solve the Case
snippet.description: Chris Carrol sat down with DJ Vlad to discuss being the responding officer at 2Pac's murder scene, and how the lack of cooperation from the superstar's entourage may have hindered the case. Cooper also discusses why he believes the case is closed, citing the death of the main suspect and lack of evidence as the main reasons. Watch above.

snippet.title: Lil Mikey TMB on His Car Getting Shot Up 100 Times, Shows Massive Scar
snippet.description: Oakland up and comer Lil Mikey TMB stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview detailing his eventful life leading up to this point. He discusses growing up in East Oakland and being the nephew of legendary Money B. He recalls times when 2Pac and Digital Underground would be at his grandmother's house when he was a child. He also discusses his past life in the streets, recalling times when he was shot and in a coma. Watch above.

snippet.title: AD & Sorry Jaynari Discuss Making Authentic West Coast Music
snippet.description: West Coast up and comers AD and Sorry Janari stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview. The pair discuss what defines west coast sound and why they believe it lost its originality as it meshed with popular sounds. AD also discusses going from a bedroom producer to a multi-platinum one as Jaynari talks about breaking through with his first big single. Watch above.

snippet.title: Greg Kading on Reggie Wright Jr Running Death Row Security
snippet.description:
Retired LAPD Detective Greg Kading shared his thoughts on the hip-hop community not trusting the police and thinking they're corrupt. He explained that certain corrupt officers give the entire police force a bad name and make people not trust them.

Moving along, Kading spoke about Death Row head of security hiring fellow police officers to help protect the record label, and what he thinks of current police activity. Hit the above clip to hear what he had to say.

snippet.title: Flashback: 7even Up Pulls Out Letter Safaree Wrote Asking Him to Ghostwrite
snippet.description: Amid, Nicki Minaj commenting on a VladTV interview where Safaree himself was called out for having a ghostwriter, we flashback to the clip that started all the recent drama. Earlier this year, 7even Up, a member of the "Hoodstars" with Nicki Minaj and Safaree, discusses his relationship with the two. He essentially goes on to call Safaree a liar for his claims that he ghostwrites for Nicki Minaj. He pulls out a letter on camera that proves that Safaree has asked him to write verses for him. Watch above.

snippet.title: Virgil Roberts on Suge Knight Bringing Dr. Dre & DOC Over Unpaid Royalties
snippet.description: Virgil Roberts of SOLAR (Sounds of Los Angeles Records) sat with DJ Vlad to discuss the history of Death Row from its inception. According to Roberts, Suge Knight brought in Dr. Dre and The D.O.C. in search of a better financial situation. Suge made it clear that "his guys" as Roberts recalls, weren't being paid at Ruthless Records for their contributions. Roberts said he asked Dr. Dre exactly how much did he contribute to the Ruthless catalog to which Dre ran down a litany of hits from N.W.A., J.J. Fad, Michel'e, and Eazy E. Roberts goes on to speak about how Dr. Dre was taught a lesson in the music business and how this eventually led to the creation of Death Row Records. He also touches on getting Dre his first publishing deal, the original name of Death Row being "Future Shock Records," and how The Chronic was recorded in the SOLAR studios.

snippet.title: Money-B on 2Pac Joining Digital Underground, Almost Quitting Rap & Joining Panthers
snippet.description: Money B of legendary rap group Digital Underground came by VladTV for an exclusive interview detailing the early days of the rap pioneers that helped launch the career of 2pac. Money B discussed meeting Pac initially and immediately knowing that there was something different by his presence. When it was time for Pac to join the group, he replaced Money B's brother - something B had no issue with. In this clip, he also talks about Pac being far more than just a dancer with Digital Underground. Watch above.

snippet.title: Napoleon (Outlawz) on 2Pac Wanting to End East Coast vs West Coast Beef
snippet.description: Napoleon Sat Down with DJ Vlad for an exclusive interview detailing the love people had for the late 2Pac and his final years. Napoleon discusses Pac's love of the East Coast and how he reached out to the East Coast OG's in an attempt to end the beef. He also talks about why people gravitated to Pac, describing his appeal to common people who were struggling in similar ways as the troubled superstar. Napoleon also cites a lack of guidance as reasoning for the inconsistency of Pac's message at times. Watch above.

snippet.title: MC Eiht Agrees with Vlad that Ice Cube in His Prime was Better than Jay-Z in His
snippet.description: West Coast veteran MC Eiht here speaks to VladTV about a recent Jay-Z shoutout, Jay-Z's reputation overall and how it compares to Ice Cube's, and the new 2Pac movie. MC Eiht agrees with Vlad that Ice Cube in his prime was a better rapper than Jay-Z in his: "Cube back in his prime was that soldier for the street music," he says. "Because even though Cube would lead you down the streets, Cube was political, Cube was, 'America, f**k that,' and, 'The streets, f**k that.'" Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: RIP Fresh Kid Ice - Uncle Luke Details Forming The 2 Live Crew
snippet.description: In remembering the life of 2 Live Crew member, Fresh Kid Ice, VladTV goes back to our 2015 sit down with Uncle Luke. In this clip, the Miami legend recalls forming the rap group, speaks on their explicit songs, and how he came up with the "Parental Advisory" sticker and failed to patent the idea.

snippet.title: Virgil Roberts on Helping Suge Knight Get a Cut of Vanilla Ice's "Ice Ice Baby"
snippet.description:
Music executive and attorney Virgil Roberts opened up about how he helped Suge Knight and his associate, Mario "Chocolate" Johnson, get a multi-million dollar settlement for writing credits on Vanilla Ice's debut album, To The Extreme. Virgil revealed that the settlement was the most amount of money Suge had made in his career up to that point.

During the conversation, Virgil said he doubted the rumors that Suge actually dangled Vanilla Ice over a hotel balcony for not getting paid for "Ice Ice Baby." He explained that Suge didn't deny the rumors over the years because it was good for his tough-guy reputation. To hear more of what Virgil had to say, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Outlawz Discuss the Events Leading Up to 2Pac Shooting 2 White Cops in Atlanta
snippet.description: Outlawz members EDI and Young Noble in the above clip describe 2Pac's legendary encounter with two white off-duty police officers in Atlanta. As EDI tells it, "A gun came out from one of the white dudes. At the time we don't know they're cops, they're just two white boys beating up a black dude. They were off-duty. So a gun come out, and Pac pulled up his shirt and was like, "Thug Life, motherf***er, shoot." And that stopped the cop in his tracks. He didn't know what to do. So he was standing next to Pac's car and he just broke the window with the butt of the gun...And then turned around and started running. And the rest is history."

snippet.title: LT Hutton Addresses Alleged Afeni Shakur Drama Over 2Pac Film
snippet.description: Director of "All Eyez On Me" and former Death Row affiliate, L.T. Hutton stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview detailing the many questions surrounding Pac's biopic. He talks about the massive budget the film had and what went in to make such an important movie. He also discusses Afeni Shakur's lack of involvement in the movie and how that changed the course of everything. Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Lisa Ann Says People Always Ask If My Big Butt Is Fake and It's Not!
snippet.description:
In 2015, Lisa Ann sat down with DJ Vlad to speak about the popularity of butt injections and implants among woman. She remembers a time where to make it in the industry every girl with get her boobs done. She then laughed at the forwardness of people who always have asked her is if her big butt is real.

Watch the clip above.

snippet.title: Andrew Schulz (Full Interview)
snippet.description:
Comedian Andrew Schulz is back on the Vlad Couch to give his hot takes on some of pop culture's current events. He and DJ Vlad speak about how they experience being called Culture Vultures, and the belief that all Americans are cultural appropriators due in part to capitalism. Andrew goes on to explain why LeBron is the best teammate and motivator of all time, how his career is unfairly compared to Michael Jordan's and the Warriors being the greatest losers in NBA History.

The first half of the interview rounds out on a more serious note as the pair discuss racial norms, and why mixed raced individuals are referred to as Black. Schulz schools Vlad on the ways the Transatlantic slave trade impacted not just racism in America but other parts of the world such as Brazil. He also explains by a person like Oprah who amassed wealth may not experience the same levels or prejudice as an everyday person of color, but suggests that money does not take away from the racism of society.

snippet.title: Flashback: Taxstone on Rob Kardashian: Tyga F'ed His Little Sister, He F'ed His Babymama
snippet.description:
Last year, famed podcaster Taxstone shared his thoughts on the Kardashian legacy, which he thinks is impressive in its own right. When asked about Blac Chyna getting with Rob Kardashian, Taxstone admitted that he thinks it's legendary. 

He told DJ Vlad, "Tyga went over there and f***ed [Rob's} little sister, so [Rob] said, 'I'm going to f*** your baby mother.'" Taxstone then added, "Rob Kardashian is out here being a whole captial G." 

Check out the full clip above.

snippet.title: Virgil Roberts on Becoming President of Solar Records, the "Motown of the '80s"
snippet.description: Accomplished record executive and attorney Virgil Roberts sat down with DJ Vlad for an unforgettable interview. In this clip, Roberts discusses being the son of a sharecropper, and how his poor upbringing shaped his future. Roberts also talks about how he became a record executive at Dick Griffey's Solar Records after initially planning to be a civil rights attorney. Watch above.

snippet.title: LT Hutton on Singleton Getting Fired for 2Pac Rape & Afeni Lesbian Scenes
snippet.description: "All Eyez on Me" producer L.T. Hutton joined VladTV to speak about the process of crafting the film, rumors that circulated about the project while it was in production, and the various personalities that he worked with along the way. On what the film demanded of its creators, Hutton said, "Anyone involved in the project couldn't be self-serving. You couldn't make it about you and what your character is. It's about 2Pac and 2Pac's voice. I had to follow the same rules because there were parts of that story that I may be in love with because they're close to me, but it's not about me. It's about giving a full understanding of an overly personified guy."

snippet.title: Greg Kading: Suge Knight Paid Orlando Anderson to Testify for Him After Attack
snippet.description: In this clip, Greg Kading spoke with DJ Vlad concerning the 2Pac murder case and the major figures within the ordeal. Kading details the particulars surrounding Keefe D's infamous confession and how this undermined Keefe D's street credibility. Kading also discusses Orlando Anderson's testimony on behalf of Suge Knight, revealing that Anderson received compensation in the tens of thousands of dollars for his testimony. He also offers his insight into Suge's current legal battles and his own descending street credibility.

snippet.title: Napoleon (Outlawz) on his Cousin Accidentally Killing Kadafi
snippet.description: Napoleon of the Outlawz here talks to VladTV about his cousin's involvement in Kadafi's accidental death, how he started drinking heavily after 2Pac's death, and his decision to leave hip hop altogether. "I was [an] alcoholic," Napoleon says. "I didn't see no happiness in that industry." Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Blac Youngsta on Getting into Shootouts for Selling $90k of Fake Bricks
snippet.description: In 2016 in his first interview with VladTV, Blac Youngsta detailed his upbringing in Memphis and how he first started to get money. "I was selling crack," Youngsta says. "It's probably one of my biggest regrets." Talking about dealing drugs, he describes selling fake bricks as a part of the hustle. Watch above.

snippet.title: Outlawz: John Singleton's a "Piece of Sh**" for 2Pac Rape Scene in Script
snippet.description: Legendary rap group Outlawz stopped by VladTV to discuss the new Tupac biopic, "All Eyez on Me." After giving credit to John Singleton as a great director, they voice their disdain on the director who worked with Pac, alluding to certain things in the script he had written. More specifically, the "Hollywood stuff" he added alluding to Pac having been raped in prison and Afeni being a lesbian in the script. Watch above.

snippet.title: First Responder Vegas Cop on Rumor that He Killed 2Pac & Switched Bodies
snippet.description: Chris Carrol, the responding officer at Tupac's murder scene, sat down with DJ Vlad to discuss events surrounding the infamous murder. Carroll speaks on the rumors floating around that he was the one who killed Pac, invalidating the claims immediately. He also describes what went on that night and how Pac's last words were "F*ck You." Watch above.

snippet.description:
Compton rapper B.G. Knocc Out details growing up with Orlando Anderson, aka "Baby Lane," who has long been accused of killing 2Pac in Las Vegas. Knocc Out refuses to detail what the now-deceased Lane had to say about his alleged involvement in 2Pac's death.

snippet.title: LT Hutton's Greatest Conversation with 2Pac was about God and Religion
snippet.description: LT Hutton revealed that his greatest conversation with Tupac centered on God and religion. According to Hutton, Pac was well versed in a multitude of religions, and this helped forge their connection due to Hutton's religious upbringing. Hutton believes Pac's level of spirituality allowed him to be unafraid of death which would explain Pac's constant references to the inevitable.

snippet.title: MC Eiht on Prodigy Dying & Mobb Deep's Impact on East Coast Gangsta Rap
snippet.description: Legendary west coast rapper MC Eiht stopped by VladTV for an exclusive interview discussing some of the contemporary issues in hip-hop. With the abrupt passing of Prodigy, Vlad and MC Eiht discuss the impact of Mobb Deep as one of the pioneers of East-Coast gangsta rap and how important health and wellness is for aging rappers. The two go on to talk about hearing different stories about the way in which Prodigy passed. Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Lisa Ann on Relationship with Rob Kardashian, His Weight Gain
snippet.description:
Flashback to this interview from 2015 when acclaimed starlet Lisa Ann where she opened up to VladTV about her relationship with Rob Kardashian and admits they had a falling out for a bit, but she's back in touch with him. The famed star says that she's trying to talk Rob into getting back into the gym, and Lisa believes his weight gain was a cry for help to his family.

During the sit-down, Lisa also lifted the veil on celebrity tapes, and says that there's no such thing as a "leaked tape." She adds that there is specific paperwork to sign in order for the footage to be made public and for sale, and there's no way it could just get "leaked" to a company.

snippet.title: Compton Gang Unit Officers on Why 2Pac's Murder is Still Unsolved
snippet.description:
Compton Gang Unit officers Timothy M. Brennan and Robert Ladd addressed why 2Pac's murder is still unsolved after 20 years, and they explained that it's Las Vegas' case. They went on to say that there is a lot of different information and lack of witness testimony in the case, making it hard for it to be solved.

Both Brennan and Ladd explained that due to their own investigation, they believe that Orlando "Baby Lane" Anderson was the shooter, which they have been saying since the beginning. To hear more, hit the above video.

snippet.title: Thug Life: Mopreme Details Smoking 2Pac's Ashes & Fulfilling Pac's Wishes
snippet.description:
Thug Life sat down for an exclusive interview with VladTV and Mopreme Shakur admitted to smoking 2Pac's ashes. He explained that it was something that 2Pac wanted and he added that it felt like a natural thing to do.

During the conversation, the group members also addressed bumping heads with Bone Thugs over the use of "thug" in their names, which they say was quickly squashed after the Ohio group met with 2Pac. They also added that they have nothing but love for Bone Thugs today. 

To hear more of what Thug Life had to say, including why fans still believe 2Pac is alive, hit the above clip.

snippet.title: Napoleon (Outlawz) on 2Pac & BIG Running Into Each Other at Height of East West Beef
snippet.description:
Former Outlawz rapper Napoleon spoke at length with VladTV about his knowledge of 2Pac's murder in Las Vegas, despite him not being with the rest of the Death Row crew at the time. During the sit-down, Napoleon would say that he heard about Diddy offering a reward for any Death Row chains being snatched for an upcoming Biggie video. The same night, 2Pac and the Death Row crew got into a heated fight with Baby Lane, who tried to snatch a chain from one of the members. 

Napoleon also spoke about how 2Pac felt Diddy had something to do with him being shot at Quad Studios, and how Keefe-D's confession matched up with what he heard. You can check out the full interview above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Lil Duval on Joking About Rob Kardashian Beating Up Blac Chyna
snippet.description: Flashback to this hilarious interview from earlier in 2017 when Lil Duval and Deray Davis stopped by to chop it up with DJ Vlad and discuss the ins and outs of Hollywood. Deray and Lil Duval go back and forth with DJ Vlad on everything from sex to weed legalization. In this clip, Duval explains some previous comments regarding Blac Chyna as Deray also touches on his relationship with DJ Vlad years before VladTV. Watch above.

snippet.title: Flashback: Calvin Klein Bacote on Getting Arrested on Attempted Murder Charges With Jay-Z
snippet.description:
Flashback to this exclusive interview from 2014 when Calvin Klein Bacote, author of Neighborhoods Under Seige, opens up about his relationship with Jay-Z, explaining that the rapper idolized him in his younger years. He then explains Jay's line, "I never felt more alive, riding shotgun in Klein's green five," from The Black Album. Klein says that the lyric is about a case they both caught in 1989 after a big fight broke out in Maryland.
Calvin says he and Jay went back and forth about who was going to take the charges after Bacote worked things out with the guy who was pressing charges, paying him $50,000. The victim said he would drop charges for one person, and Calvin saw potential in Jay's career and decided to do the time.
After Jay testified on his behalf, Calvin got four years on an assault charge but didn't hear from the Brooklyn rapper for several years until making a phone call to their mutual friend Ty Ty Smith. When Jay anxiously wanted to talk to Bacote on the other line, the now-author hung up and said he never called again. Calvin said that he made the decision because he didn't want to get Jay tangled in drama over the recorded phone call.

snippet.title: Greg Nice on Living with 2Pac, People Comparing 2Pac to Bob Marley
snippet.description: Bronx MC Greg Nice talked with VladTV detailing his experience at Death Row and the environment of the label at the time. He spoke about how the Death Row he experienced was different from that of popular perception. Greg Nice spent the majority of his time at Death Row with 2Pac and Tha Outlawz where he was able to witness Pac's "amazing work ethic." He went as far as to call Pac a 'mad man' for the how much he worked. Many attribute Pac foreshadowing his death to work ethic, something Greg Nice was unwilling to commit to. In addition to his Pac and Death Row stories, Greg Nice also expanded on Ky-Mani Marley's comparison of Pac to his father Bob Marley, championing the social impact of Pac's music. Greg Nice spoke about his relationship to the late Phife Dawg of A Tribe Called Quest and the sad trend of rappers dying in their 40s.

snippet.title: Cash Kidd on Why He Thinks Detroit was Blackballed from the Rap Game
snippet.description: Up and coming rapper Cash Kidd came all the way from Detroit for an exclusive interview with VLadTV. In this clip, Cash Kidd discusses his hit single "On My Momma" going viral overnight, and how his life has changed since. He also discusses the rap scene in Detroit and how his hometown can be a hateful city at times, changing how he interacts and moves around. Watch above.

snippet.title: Rico Nasty on Linking Up with Lil Yachty on Vine, Making Music Together
snippet.description:
DMV rapper Rico Nasty spoke with VladTV about her come up after "iCarly" went viral online, and she shared some things that she's learned in the process.
Rico went through the learning process of keeping people at a distance because they like to cling on to people with fame, and she added that she's been lucky enough to only deal with one sexist situation as a female rapper so far. To hear more of what Rico Nasty had to say, including how she linked up with Lil Yachty, hit the above clip.
